'''Mary Dillon''' (born 1964), is an Irish [[folk music|folk]] singer, known for her work with the traditional band [[D<U+00E9>anta]]. She launched her solo career in 2010 with the release of an EP entitled ''[[Army Dreamers (Mary Dillon EP)|Army Dreamers]]''. She is the sister of singer [[Cara Dillon]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/d5fbea2e-8d7d-4511-b1b9-332bd6d9a64c BBC - Music - Mary Dillon]. Retrieved on 2010-08-11.</ref>

==Early life==

Mary Dillon was born in [[Dungiven]], where she still lives with her two children, a son and a daughter. She was raised in a musical household and one of her five siblings is fellow folk singer [[Cara Dillon]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/d5fbea2e-8d7d-4511-b1b9-332bd6d9a64c BBC - Music - Mary Dillon]. Retrieved on 2010-08-11.</ref> She has never pursued singing as a full-time career and currently works as an English teacher at [[St Cecilia's College]] in [[Derry]].<ref>[http://www.stceciliascollege.com/Department_Personnel.aspx St Cecilia's College, Derry - Department Personnel]. Retrieved on 2010-08-11.</ref>

==Music career==

Mary Dillon started singing at an early age and by her mid-teens, she had twice won the All Ireland Singing Competition at [[Fleadh Cheoil|Fleadh Cheoil na h<U+00C9>ireann]].<ref>[http://www.marydillon.com/biography/ Mary Dillon > Biography]. Retrieved on 2012-11-16.</ref>

In the 1990s, she recorded three albums with the Irish traditional band [[D<U+00E9>anta]].<ref>[http://greenlinnet.com/artist.php?id=213 Green Linnet > D<U+00E9>anta]. Retrieved on 2010-08-11.</ref>

In 2010, she released a digital-only EP containing covers of ''[[Army Dreamers]]'' by [[Kate Bush]], ''Undone in Sorrow'' by [[Ola Belle Reed]] and ''[[Streets of Philadelphia]]'' by [[Bruce Springsteen]].<ref>[http://www.backlanemusic.com/discography/ Discography <U+00AB> Back Lane Music]. Retrieved on 2010-08-11.</ref>

In 2012, she joined fellow Irish folk singers [[Niamh Parsons]] and [[Tamalin (band)|T<U+00ED>ona McSherry]] to form an a cappella group called [[S<U+00ED> Van]].<ref>[http://www.derryjournal.com/lifestyle/entertainment/irish-masters-at-ulster-fleadh-2012-1-4077858 Irish Masters at Ulster Fleadh 2012]. Retrieved on 2012-11-12.</ref>

== Discography ==

=== Solo ===
* ''[[Army Dreamers (Mary Dillon EP)|Army Dreamers]]'' (EP) (2010)
* ''[[North (Mary Dillon album)|North]]'' (Album) (2013)

=== As a member of D<U+00E9>anta ===
* ''D<U+00E9>anta'' (1993)
* ''Ready for the Storm'' (1994)
* ''Whisper of a Secret'' (1997)

=== Collaborations and guest appearances ===
* Cara Dillon - ''[[Cara Dillon (album)|Cara Dillon]]'' (2001)
* Cara Dillon - ''[[Sweet Liberty (album)|Sweet Liberty]]'' (2003)
* Eamon Friel - ''Waltz of the Years'' (2003)
* Various Artists - ''Boys of the Island'' (2005)
* Cara Dillon - ''[[After the Morning (Cara Dillon album)|After the Morning]]'' (2006)
* Cara Dillon - ''[[The Redcastle Sessions]]'' (2008)
* Eamon Friel - ''Smarter'' (2009)
* Sullem Voe - ''All Naked Flames'' (2009)

